This may be a simple question but still I am confused about how to do the following in the context of react redux. 

I have 2 screens - Root screen and Home screen. 
When user taps on Home screen I load the data from local device storage and map this data to the props of Root screen. 
On root screen's render I then show the data via a state, and also bind props and actions from Home screen to state of root screen. 

Then in another screen called Detail, when I call useContext or use the state of root I am unable to call props. This works fine in one screen but not in other. 

What is the best practice to bind and use state from another screen ? It would be great if it can be done without a context and with the use of redux. (as you cannot use redux to pass a state from one screen to another without a context)

P.S. I have created an example on codeSandbox
To bind and use state from another screen, you need to use the `useContext` hook from the `react-redux` library. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```
import { useContext, useEffect } from 'react';
import { useSelector, useDispatch } from 'react-redux';

// Redux action definitions
export const LOAD_DATA = 'LOAD_DATA';
export const UPDATE_DATA = 'UPDATE_DATA';

// Redux reducer
const initialState = {
  data: [],
};

const reducer = (state = initialState, action) => {
  switch (action.type) {
    case LOAD_DATA:
      return {
        ...state,
        data: action.payload,
      };
    case UPDATE_DATA:
      return {
        ...state,
        data: action.payload,
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
};

const App = () => {
  const dispatch = useDispatch();
  const data = useSelector(state => state.data);
  const loading = useSelector(state => state.loading);

  useEffect(() => {
    dispatch({ type: LOAD_DATA });
  }, [dispatch]);

  if (loading) {
    return <p>Loading...</p>;
  }

  return (
    <div>
      {data.map(item => (
        <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

